arrayOf("Pawar / Panwar","पवार / पंवार","Panwar Gurjars: History, Tradition, and Legacy\nThe Panwar (Parmar) Gurjars are regarded as one of the most ancient and influential lineages within the wider Gurjar community. Their identity is shaped by a mix of mythological tradition, recorded medieval history, and modern anthropological debates.\nOrigin Traditions\nAccording to traditional Gurjar chronicles, the Panwars are counted among the Agnivanshi clans, believed to have originated from Mount Abu.\nThe legend states that a sage (rishi) performed a yagya (sacred fire ritual), from which warrior lineages emerged to protect dharma. The Panwars are said to be born from this sacred fire .\n\nEthnic and Genetical Data \nModern researchers and some independent genetic discussions claim that many Gurjar groups, including Panwars, show strong presence of R1a (Indo-Aryan) Y-haplogroup, commonly associated with early Indo-European populations.\nThere are also theories linking Gurjars to White Huns (Hephthalites) \nOr Aryans .\nPanwars genetics physical +mental potential model is more Similarly to other Gurjar clan like Hun , chawri , siradhana etc.\n\n\nRoyal and Warrior Lineage\nHistorically, Panwar Gurjars produced powerful rulers, warriors, and administrators, especially in Malwa, Dhar, Ujjain, and western Uttar Pradesh.( Haridwar capital) , kutch , gujrat etc.\nNotable figures traditionally associated with the Panwar lineage include:\nVeer Vikramajeet (Vikramaditya) – legendary ruler of Ujjain\nRaja Bharthari – king turned yogi, brother of Vikramaditya\nMainavati – sister of Vikramaditya, mother of Raja Gopichand, a major Nath yogi figure\nRaja Bhoj of Dhar – one of legendry and powerful kings of Gurjars clan .\nRaja Jagdev, Udaybhan, and Dharanivarah – rulers linked with the Malwa - dhar region\nRaja Jaidev – father of Peepal Devi, wife of Shri Devnarayan, a major Gurjar folk deity\nThese names appear across folk literature, inscriptions, and regional histories, especially in Rajasthan, Madhya Pradesh, and western UP.\nAnd From Dhar they spilited \nSome goes to Haridwar , some kutch , some Gujrat\nIt is also beleived that \nLohiya / lohmod - from king jagdev panwar ( bend 60 kg rod in pushkar) \nBaisla - from king jasdul ( ravindra baisla sahab video is available on youtube ) \nBidhuri amd rekshwal also originate from panwars \n\nResistance and Warfare\nThe Panwar Gurjars were not only rulers but also frontline military leaders.\nSenapati Jograj Singh Panwar ( Haridwar) is remembered for resisting Timur’s forces, reflecting Gurjar military resistance during medieval invasions.\nPanwar groups maintained armed control over large rural belts and pilgrimage routes, including movements toward Haridwar \nKutch , Gujrat ( Shree Gurjar Kshtriya katriya samaj ) \nTerritories \nHaridwar reigion :-\nBelieved that there capital was haridwar at that time \nPanwar Gurjars historically dominated an area of 84 villages stretching from:\nYamuna region (Yamunanagar, Karnal)\nto\nGanga–Garh region (Bijnor, Garh Ganga)\n\nImportant villages include:\nVeer Miragpur – traditionally founded on land blessed by Yogi Gareebnath\nJandkhera – named after the sacred Jand tree, associated with historical conflicts between Gurjars and muslim\nJandhera - beleived to act as a backhand of kunwars of haridwar \nLakshar , landhora etc. \n\nThese villages functioned as military, agricultural, and cultural units,forming a strong Gurjar belt.\nPresent Legacy\nGurjars panwars are also present in some part of gujrat , kutch reigion and mp also ( but unable to found their real data ) \nThe legacy of Panwar Gurjars continues today through regional leadership and estates such as:\nLandhora Riyasat, associated with Raja Parnav Singh Panwar\nWhile princely power has ended, social influence, land control, and cultural pride remain strong.\nFinal Raw Assessment\nPanwar Gurjars are undeniably ancient and influential.\nTheir royal and warrior legacy is real, even if some early origins are legendary \n\nKhaps:- \nKhubar , Dhakad , nagad beleived from one baba \nTat or tatarne these khaps sources are from haridwar bhats \n\nSome confusions :-\nPanwars - same gotra appear in rajput , jaat, jogi and many more tribal group \nYes , but many more tribal group and jogi have pawar , pawaar, puwar , pawara their pronunciation is almost same but not same as Panwars in Gurjars they have their own history or lineage seprately some merges or confusion due to mistakes or pride seeking during british era \nJaat have pawar and in north india some time written as panwar \nBut they are chandravanshi most of their story and myths lineage are separate \nIn rajput so they are closest to Gurjars i am not criticising or praise anyone but \nThey also have same stories and pride about panwars but different social and lineage stories ( here i am talking about rajputs in rajasthan some rajputs earlier take title due to pride seeking even when they are not belongs to any Gurjar or rajput lineage and now fought for their so called history ) \nIn rajputs they mention sodha or sankla but not ,mention any gurjars khap and same in gurjars .","SG"),
